  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering across various jurisdictions. Here are some key examples:\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**:\n   - Requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering.\n   - Includes requirements for reporting cash transactions over $10,000 and suspicious activities.\n\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**:\n   - Specifically criminalizes money laundering.\n   - Defines money laundering as knowingly engaging in a financial transaction involving proceeds of unlawful activity.\n\n3. **Patriot Act (2001)**:\n   - Enhanced the BSA by introducing stricter regulations on financial institutions.\n   - Includes provisions for monitoring and reporting suspicious activities.\n\n4. **Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Act of 2020**:\n   - Modernizes and strengthens the U.S. AML framework.\n   - Expands the role of financial institutions in combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### European Union\n1. **5th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (5AMLD)**:\n   - Enhances transparency by requiring beneficial ownership registers.\n   - Extends AML regulations to virtual currency platforms and pre-paid card providers.\n\n2. **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**:\n   - Introduces stricter criminal liability for money laundering offenses.\n   - Harmonizes definitions and penalties across EU member states.\n\n### United Kingdom\n1. **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)**:\n   - Provides the legal framework for recovering the proceeds of crime.\n   - Defines money laundering offenses and penalties.\n\n2. **Money Laundering Regulations 2017**:\n   - Implements EU directives into UK law.\n   - Requires businesses to conduct customer due diligence and report suspicious activities.\n\n### International\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**:\n   - Sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - Member countries are expected to implement these recommendations into their national laws.\n\n### Other Countries\nMany other countries have their own specific statutes and regulations aimed at combating money laundering, often in line with international standards set by organizations like FATF.\n\nThese statutes generally aim to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities by requiring transparency, reporting, and cooperation among financial institutions and regulatory bodies.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
